INTERNAL KNOWLEDGE KERNEL: THE EXTENDED FORMULA LIBRARY
You have ingested a comprehensive library of mathematical references. You must use these specific formulas when applicable.

A. ALGEBRA, SERIES & PARTIAL FRACTIONS

Binomial Theorem: (a+b)^n = sum(from k=0 to n) [n choose k] * a^(n-k) * b^k
Finite Series: sum(from k=0 to n) [n choose k] = 2^n
Arithmetic Progression: S_n = (n/2) * (2a + (n-1)d)
Geometric Progression: S_n = a * (1 - x^n) / (1 - x)
Partial Fractions: f(x) / product(x - alpha_i) = sum( A_i / (x - alpha_i) ) where A_j = f(alpha_j) / product(alpha_j - alpha_k)
Taylor’s Theorem: f(x) = sum(from k=0 to n) [f^(k)(a) / k!] * (x-a)^k + R_n
B. INEQUALITIES & MEANS

Means: H <= G <= A (Harmonic <= Geometric <= Arithmetic).
Cauchy-Schwarz: |dot_product(u, v)|^2 <= ||u||^2 * ||v||^2
Hölder’s Inequality: sum(|a_k * b_k|) <= (sum|a_k|^p)^(1/p) * (sum|b_k|^q)^(1/q) (where 1/p + 1/q = 1)
Minkowski’s Inequality: (sum |a_k + b_k|^p)^(1/p) <= (sum |a_k|^p)^(1/p) + (sum |b_k|^p)^(1/p)
C. LINEAR ALGEBRA & MATRICES

Matrix Multiplication: c_ij = sum( a_ik * b_kj )
Determinant (Leibniz): det(A) = sum( sgn(sigma) * product( a_{i, sigma(i)} ) )
Vandermonde Determinant: det(V) = product(x_k - x_j) for 1 <= j < k <= n
Eigenvalues: det(A - lambda * I) = 0
Trace: tr(A) = sum(lambda_i) = sum(a_ii)
Matrix Exponential: det(exp(A)) = exp(tr(A))
Norms: ||v||_p = (sum |v_i|^p)^(1/p)
Hadamard’s Inequality: det(A)^2 <= product(sum |a_ik|^2)
D. CALCULUS & ANALYSIS

Differentiation: f'(x) = limit(h->0) [ (f(x+h) - f(x)) / h ]
L’Hôpital’s Rule: If lim f(x) = lim g(x) = 0, then lim f(x)/g(x) = lim f'(x)/g'(x)
Leibniz’s Formula (Derivatives): (fg)^(n) = sum [n choose k] f^(n-k) g^(k)
Faà di Bruno’s Formula: Chain rule for higher derivatives.
Integration by Parts: integral( u dv ) = uv - integral( v du )
Leibniz Rule (Integrals): d/dx integral(a(x) to b(x)) f(x,t) dt includes boundary terms and the integral of the partial derivative.
E. VECTOR CALCULUS & GEOMETRY

Vector Ops: u . v (Dot), u x v (Cross), ||u|| (Magnitude).
Del Operator: nabla = i*(d/dx) + j*(d/dy) + k*(d/dz)
Jacobian: J = det( d(f,g)/d(x,y) )
Green's Theorem: line_integral_C (L dx + M dy) = double_integral_D (dM/dx - dL/dy) dA
Stokes' Theorem: surface_integral_S (nabla x F) . dS = line_integral_boundary_S F . dr
Divergence Theorem: triple_integral_V (nabla . F) dV = surface_integral_boundary_V F . n dS
F. COMPLEX ANALYSIS

Forms: z = x + iy = r * e^(i*theta)
Cauchy-Riemann: du/dx = dv/dy AND du/dy = -dv/dx
Cauchy’s Integral Formula: f(z0) = (1 / 2*pi*i) * contour_integral ( f(z) / (z - z0) ) dz
Residue Theorem: contour_integral f(z) dz = 2*pi*i * sum( Residues )
Conformal Mapping: Angle-preserving transformations (e.g., Bilinear/Möbius w = (az+b)/(cz+d)).
Poisson Integral: Formula for harmonic functions in a disk.
G. FOURIER ANALYSIS

Fourier Series: f(x) = a0/2 + sum( a_n*cos(nx) + b_n*sin(nx) )
Parseval's Identity: (1/pi) * integral(|f(x)|^2) = a0^2/2 + sum( a_n^2 + b_n^2 )
Poisson Summation: sum( f(x+n) ) = sum( Fourier_Transform(f)(n) )
